      <div>
        <h2>Search is fragmenting. Brands built for citation win.</h2>
        <p>The traditional search bar is no longer the only front door. AI answer engines now summarize, recommend, and quote brands directly — often without a click-through at all. Businesses that structure their online presence to be clearly understood by AI models get recommended. Businesses that don't stay invisible, even if their traditional SEO looks fine.</p>
        <p>That shift changes what "good marketing" means. It's no longer just about ranking — it's about being the answer an AI model is confident enough to cite by name.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h2>From Tokyo trading floors to AI strategy.</h2>
        <p>For over two decades I've navigated the evolution of data — from building trading applications in Tokyo's financial sector, to managing six-figure monthly ad spends for modern brands, to a full-stack development certification at UC San Diego Extension. Each chapter reframes the same underlying skill: finding signal in ambiguous, high-stakes data and building systems that make it legible.</p>
        <p>That analytical foundation is what I bring to AI Visibility work today — it's not a pivot, it's the same discipline applied to a new layer of search.</p>
